Chapter 6: The Announcement
They returned to Kumogakure as dawn broke over the mountains, their
prisoners secured, their report prepared, their hands clasped together where
anyone could see. The village was waking, the dark majority beginning their
daily routines, the white minority stirring in their privileged compounds.
Darui received them in his private chambers, his expression unreadable as
he listened to their report. When they finished, he sat in silence for a long
moment, his fingers steepled beneath his chin.
"Iwa has been playing a long game," he said finally. "Using our own divisions
against us. It's clever. Cruel, but clever."
"We can use this," Nanzo said. "The prisoners will talk. We can trace their
network, expose the other agents, turn their strategy back on them."
"And the personal element?" Darui's eyes moved between them, noting their
joined hands, the matching bruises, the way they stood slightly too close.
"The blackmail attempt, the threat to Karui-san?"
"Was unsuccessful." Nanzo's grip tightened on her fingers. "As it will always
be unsuccessful. I am making a formal declaration, Darui-sama. Karui and I
are... together. Partners. In all things. Anyone who threatens her threatens
me, and I will respond with the full force of the Anitsu Clan."
"Your mother?"
"Will learn to accept it. Or she will learn to live with disappointment." Nanzo's
voice was steel. "I am clan head. My choices are mine to make. And I choose
her."
Darui studied them for a long moment, then smiledthat rare, genuine
expression that transformed his face from lazy politician to legendary shinobi.
"About time," he said. "The village has been taking bets on when you'd make
it official. I had three weeks from today in the pool."
Karui felt her jaw drop. "You knew?"
"Everyone knew, kid." Darui rose, moving to the window. "The way you two
look at each other? It's not subtle. The only question was whether Nanzo
would grow the spine to admit it publicly." He turned back, his expression
serious. "But know thismaking it official changes things. The white minority
will react. There will be pressure, gossip, maybe threats. Are you prepared for
that?"
"We are," they said together, and Karui felt the rightness of it, the unity that
made them stronger than either could be alone.
"Then go," Darui said. "Make your announcement. Deal with the fallout. And
when you're ready, come back to me with a plan for rooting out Iwa's network.
We'll need the Anitsu Clan's unique capabilities and your partner's particular
skills."
They left the Raikage's tower into the full morning light, and Nanzo turned to
her with a question in his eyes. "Publicly?" he asked. "Now?"
"Now," she confirmed. "No more hiding. No more pretending to be allies or
teacher and student. We walk through the village together, and we let them
see."
They walked.
Through the market districts, where dark-skinned vendors called out
greetings to Karui and fell silent when they saw her hand in Nanzo's. Through
the training grounds, where Killer B looked up from his rap practice and
flashed them a thumbs-up that suggested he had known all along. Through
the administrative quarter, where white minority officials stared and whispered
and turned away with expressions of disgust.
Karui held her head high, her amber eyes challenging anyone who dared
meet her gaze. She was dark, she was stubborn, she was loud, and she was
loved by the most powerful clan head in Kumogakure. Let them whisper. Let
the thirty percent feel their minority status acutely, surrounded by the seventy
percent who looked like her and accepted her as one of their own.
At the Anitsu compound gates, they paused. Nora would be inside, preparing
breakfast, perhaps, or arranging flowers, or engaging in any of the countless
rituals that maintained the illusion of a world that no longer existed.
"Together," Nanzo said.
"Together," she agreed.
They entered.
---
Nora met them in the main hall, her posture perfect, her face a mask of polite
inquiry. But Karui saw the moment she noticed their joined hands, the slight
widening of her yellow eyes, the way her fingers tightened on the fan she
carried.
"Nanzo," she said, her voice carefully neutral. "You're back early. I wasn't
expecting you until"
"Mom." He released Karui's hand, but only to place his arm around her
shoulders, drawing her close.
"Karui and I have something to tell you. Something the village will know by
nightfall."
Nora's fan snapped open, hiding the lower half of her face. "I see."
"We're together. Romantically. Partners in life as well as combat." He spoke
quickly, as if speed could soften the blow. "I love her. She loves me. We're
going to build a future together, here in this compound, with the clan. And I
need you to accept that. Not just tolerate itaccept it. Because she is going
to be my wife, and the mother of my children, and your daughter-in-law, and I
will not have her treated as anything less than family."
The silence stretched between them, heavy and dangerous. Karui felt Nora's
eyes on her, assessing, judging, seeing all the things she had always seen:
dark skin, stubborn jaw, loud presence, the pollution of purity.
Then Nora closed her fan. Her hands were trembling.
"You've made your choice," she said, her voice barely above a whisper.
"I have."
"And if I cannot accept it? If I look at her and see everything that will destroy
what your father died to protect?"
"Then you will lose me too." Nanzo's voice was gentle but unyielding. "I don't
want that. I love you, Mom. You've raised me, trained me, been my family
when I had no one. But I am not a child anymore. I am clan head, and I
choose her. I choose life and change and a future that isn't defined by blood
purity and extinct traditions. And if that choice excludes you, I will grieve. But I
will not change it."
Nora looked at himreally lookedand Karui saw something break in her
expression. The mask of the perfect mother, the guardian of purity, cracked to
reveal the woman beneath: afraid, grieving, loving her son so much that it
had become a kind of poison.
"I need time," Nora said finally. "Time to... to understand. To see what you
see in her."
"Take the time you need." Nanzo stepped forward, embracing his mother, and
Karui saw Nora stiffen before slowly, reluctantly, returning the gesture. "But
know that she is part of my life now. Part of our family. And I believe, if you let
yourself, you could come to love her too."
Nora's eyes met Karui's over Nanzo's shoulder, and in them Karui saw no
love, no acceptanceonly a desperate, drowning fear. But there was
something else too, something that might grow into tolerance, if not affection:
the recognition that Karui loved him too, that she had risked her life for him,
that she was not the monster Nora had imagined.
"We'll see," Nora said. And for now, that was enough.

Chapter 7: The Wedding of Waves
Six months later, Kumogakure celebrated the wedding of Nanzo Anitsu and
Karui of the Hidden Cloud.
It was not the wedding the white minority had envisioned for their precious
Prince. There was no weeks-long purification ritual, no exclusive guest list of
pale-skinned nobility, no emphasis on the preservation of bloodline purity.
Instead, the ceremony was held in the village's central plaza, open to all, with
Darui himself officiating and Killer B providing entertainment that was
arguably inappropriate for a formal occasion.
Karui wore whitea deliberate choice, a claiming of the color that had always
been used to exclude her. Her dress was simple, cut for movement rather
than display, and she carried her sword instead of flowers. Her skin glowed
dark against the silk, her amber eyes defiant, her red hair crowned with a
circlet of silver waves that Nanzo had designed himself.
Nanzo wore black. The color of the majority, of the village that had raised her,
of the future they were building together. His white skin seemed to shine
against it, his yellow eyes bright with an emotion that made Karui's heart
ache. Around his neck, visible to all, was the scar from her bitethe mark she
had given him when he was helpless, now displayed as proudly as any
medal.
The vows they wrote themselves, rejecting the traditional Anitsu Clan
language of purity and preservation in favor of something new:
"I take you not to maintain what was, but to create what will be," Nanzo said,
his voice carrying across the silent crowd. "Not as master and servant, not as
purity and pollution, but as partners. Equals. Two waves that meet and merge
and become something stronger than either alone."
"I take you not despite your darkness, but because of it," Karui replied, her
voice steady despite the tears she refused to shed. "Not to tame you or
change you, but to grow with you. To fight beside you, to challenge you, to
love you in all your complicated, stubborn, beautiful humanity."
When they kissed, the crowd erupteddark-skinned majority cheering their
own, white minority watching in stunned silence, the village acknowledging
that something fundamental had shifted. The Anitsu Clan was no longer an
isolated bastion of purity. It was changing, adapting, becoming part of the
larger world.
And in the front row, Nora Anitsu stood with her hands clasped so tightly that
her knuckles were white, watching her son smile in a way she had never
seen before, watching the dark girl who had somehow made him whole, and
tryingtruly tryingto find happiness in his happiness.
Later, at the reception, she approached Karui alone. The new bride was
watching Nanzo dance with Killer Ban absurd spectacle that involved too
much enthusiasm and questionable rhythmand her expression was soft in a
way that Nora had never seen directed at her.
"Karui-san," Nora said, the honorific feeling strange in her mouth.
"Nora-san." Karui turned, her defenses immediately rising, her body shifting
into a combat-ready stance that was probably unconscious.
"I wanted to give you something." Nora held out a small box, her hands
steady through sheer force of will. "It belonged to Nanzo's mother. She wore
it on her wedding day, and her mother before her. I had thought... I had hoped
to give it to a bride who matched our... our standards. But I was wrong. About
many things."
Karui took the box, opening it to reveal a necklacesimple, elegant, a
pendant shaped like a wave that seemed to move when the light hit it. "It's
beautiful."
"It is tradition," Nora said carefully. "But tradition can change. You are
changing it. And I am trying to change with it. For him. Because he loves you,
and I love him, and perhaps... perhaps that is enough."
Karui looked at herreally lookedand saw the effort it cost, the battle that
Nora was fighting against her own prejudice, her own fear. It wasn't
acceptance. It wasn't even true tolerance. But it was a beginning.
"Thank you," Karui said, and meant it. She fastened the necklace around her
throat, the wave pendant resting against her dark skin, and saw Nora's eyes
widen slightly at the contrastthe white gold against her complexion, the
traditional symbol worn in a new way. "I'll take care of him. I promise. Not
because he needs protecting, but because we protect each other."
"I know," Nora whispered. "I have seen it. In the laboratory, when you ran into
the resonance field. In the missions, when you fight together. You make him
stronger. I cannot deny that, even when I wish to."
She turned to leave, but Karui stopped her with a hand on her arm. "Nora-
san. I don't expect you to love me. I don't even expect you to like me. But I
hope, someday, you might respect me. As a shinobi, as a partner to your son,
as someone who is trying to build something good in this broken world."
Nora looked at the hand on her armdark fingers against her white sleeve,
the physical reality of their difference that she had always found so
threatening. Then she did something that surprised them both: she covered
Karui's hand with her own, briefly, a gesture of acknowledgment.
"Respect," she said, tasting the word. "Yes. I think... I think I can manage
respect. In time."
She left then, moving through the crowd toward the compound's quiet interior,
and Karui watched her go with complex emotions. The war wasn't over. Nora
still looked at her and saw darkness, still feared the future, still struggled with
the minority's terror of being overwhelmed. But there was a truce now, a
space for possibility, and that was more than Karui had expected.
"She spoke to you." Nanzo appeared at her side, slightly breathless from
dancing, his yellow eyes concerned.
"She gave me your mother's necklace." Karui touched the pendant. "And she
promised to try. That's something, isn't it?"
"That's everything." He drew her into his arms, beginning to move with the
music, his body swaying against hers. "Thank you. For being patient with her.
For not giving up on this family, even when it would be easier to walk away."
"I don't walk away from fights," Karui reminded him, resting her head against
his shoulder. "And I don't walk away from you. We're partners, remember?
Stubborn, damaged, complicated partners, bound by teeth marks and training
sessions and the stubborn refusal to be what everyone expects."
"Till death," he whispered.
"And beyond," she promised.
The music swelled around them, the celebration of a village that was learning
to change, and in the center of the dance floor, dark and pale, stubborn and
scared, they moved together as one.

VOLUME II: THE SHADOWS OF SHIBAI

Chapter 8: The Secret of Origins
One year after the wedding, Nanzo stood in the deepest chamber of the
Anitsu compound , a space that existed on no map and was known only to
the clan head. The walls were covered in seals that predated the village itself,
written in a language that was not quite of this world, describing truths that
could break minds unprepared for them.
He was not supposed to bring anyone here. The secret of the Anitsu Clan's
origin was for the clan head alone, passed down through generations in a
chain of knowledge that stretched back to the tsutsuki themselves.
But Karui stood beside him, her hand in his, and he had promised her
partnership in all things.
"Shibai tsutsuki," he said, his voice echoing in the sealed space. "The
progenitor. The source of our Wave Style, our yellow eyes, our connection to
the fundamental forces of the universe. Our bloodline is not just a mutation or
evolutionit is inheritance. Direct, unbroken, from a being that transcended
this world."
Karui stared at the walls, at the images that seemed to move when viewed
from the corner of one's eye. "You're saying your clan is descended from
gods?"
"From one god. One who experimented on this world, who left behind
fragments of power that became what we call Kekkei Genkai." Nanzo
touched the central seal, feeling it pulse in recognition of his blood. "The
Uchiha have their Sharingan from another branch. The Hyga their
Byakugan. And we... we have the waves. The ability to manipulate the
fundamental vibrations of reality."
"Why are you telling me this?" Karui turned to face him, her amber eyes
serious. "This is clan head knowledge. Sacred, secret, all those things."
"Because there is more." He led her to a pedestal at the chamber's center,
upon which rested a scroll that seemed to absorb light rather than reflect it.
"The Waver Mode. Our ultimate technique. Only two people in history have
ever used itthe founder, and potentially me."
He unrolled the scroll, revealing diagrams that made Karui's head ache to
look at. Chakra pathways that shouldn't exist, techniques that required the
user to become something other than human, to merge with the wave nature
of reality itself.
"It grants godlike power," Nanzo continued, his voice hollow. "Control over all
waves within a twohundred-kilometer radius. Chakra, sound,
electromagnetic, seismiceverything. For thirty minutes, the user is
effectively invincible. And then they die. The body cannot sustain that level of
transformation. It burns out, consumes itself, leaves nothing but ash."
Karui felt cold fear spread through her chest. "You've never used it."
"No."
"And you never will."
Nanzo was silent.
"Nanzo." She grabbed his shoulders, forcing him to look at her. "Promise me.
Promise me you will never use this. Not for the village, not for me, not for
anything. Promise me."
"I can't promise that." His eyes were wet, desperate. "If the village is
destroyed, if you're threatened, if there's no other way... Karui, I would give
anything to protect you. Even my life. Especially my life."
"Then find another way!" She shook him, her temper breaking through.
"You're the smartest person I know. You understand physics, chakra
dynamics, sealing techniques that no one else has even imagined. Find
another way to be strong that doesn't involve killing yourself!"
"I'm trying!" He pulled her close, burying his face in her hair, his body
shaking. "I'm trying, Karui. I've been researching alternatives, training to
increase my base power, developing new techniques so I'll never need the
Waver Mode. But I need you to understandif it comes to that choice, if it's
the only way to save you, I will use it. And I need you to forgive me in
advance for that choice."
She held him, feeling his fear and his love and his desperate, stubborn
willingness to sacrifice everything for her safety. And she made a silent vow,
there in the chamber of secrets, that she would never let that choice become
necessary. That she would fight beside him, protect him, challenge him to find
another way, until the day they both died of old age in each other's arms.
"I don't forgive you," she said finally. "But I understand you. And I will fight you
on this, Nanzo. Every day, every mission, every threat. I will be strong
enough that you never need to consider that scroll. I will be your partner in
truth, not just in words."
"That's all I ask," he whispered. "Just... stay with me. Keep me human. Keep
me from becoming a god, even when the power tempts me."
"I promise," she said. And unlike his impossible promise, hers was one she
knew she could keep.
They both sleep in bed.
Atmosphere: Pre-dawn darkness, rain against windows, Nanzo and Karui
asleep in shared bed
The Descent
Nanzo was dreaming of waves.
Not the violent, destructive waves of his clan's techniques, but gentle ocean
wavesrhythmic, eternal, the sound his mother must have heard in the
womb before she died protecting him. He was floating in an endless golden
sea, weightless, peaceful.
Then the sea turned inside out.
The water became sky. The sky became flesh. Nanzo found himself standing
on a surface that was simultaneously stone, cloud, and the surface of an
eyemassive, lidless, blinking in slow, geological time.
He knew this place.
The tsutsuki Dimension. The realm of gods.
"Finally."
The voice didn't speakit resonated. It vibrated through every atom of
Nanzo's being, making his teeth ache, his bones hum, his Wave Style chakra
scream in recognition. This was no Genjutsu. No ordinary mind technique.
This was a direct neural transmission from a being that existed beyond
conventional reality.
Nanzo turned.
Shibai tsutsuki stoodor rather, existedbefore him.
The progenitor of the Anitsu Clan's secret bloodline. The being whose divine
DNA had been passed down through centuries, mutating into the Wave Style
Kekkei Genkai. The god who had abandoned his mortal shell to become pure
chakra, pure will, pure hunger.
He had no fixed form. He was a silhouette of golden light and absolute
darkness, shifting between humanoid shapes and geometric impossibilities
sometimes with horns, sometimes with the Rinnegan's concentric rings,
sometimes with nothing at all but a pressure that made Nanzo's soul want to
kneel.
"Nanzo Anitsu." The name was a caress and a command. "My youngest
son's most stubborn descendant. Do you know how long I have watched
you?"
Nanzo's hands moved instinctively to form seals, but he had no hands here
only concept. He was thought. He was dream-stuff. He was vulnerable.
"Since your mother burned herself to protect you." Shibai's form flickered,
showing a ghost-image of Nyoko's Final Resonanceher body dissolving into
golden light. "Such waste. Such delicious, desperate waste. She could have
been so much more."
"Don't you DARE speak of her." Nanzo's voicehis dream-voicecrackled
with Wave Style resonance. Even here, even disembodied, his chakra
remembered its nature. The golden sea around them rippled with his anger.
Shibai laughed. The sound was supernovas dying. It was the silence between
heartbeats. It was every nightmare Nanzo had ever suppressed since the
massacre.
"Brave. Foolish. You have always been my favorite flavor of descendant." The
god-thing circled him, leaving trails of stardust and decay. "Do you know why
the Uchiha truly attacked your clan? Why Fugaku feared you?"
Nanzo said nothing. His dream-heart was pounding.
"Because I whispered to him." Shibai's voice dropped to an intimate, horrible
intimacy. "In his Mangeky dreams. I showed him the future where Anitsu
Clan children grew strong enough to disrupt not just Genjutsu... but Divine
Techniques. The techniques of gods. My techniques."
The revelation hit Nanzo like a physical blow. "You... you caused the
massacre?"
"I encouraged it." Shibai's form split into a smile with too many teeth. "Your
clan was becoming too numerous. Too visible. The Wave Style was evolving
beyond my designyour mother's Final Resonance touched the edges of my
power. That could not be allowed. Better to cull the herd, leave only the
strongest..."
He reached out with fingers that were also galaxies, also swords, also the
hands of Nanzo's dead father.
"...and guide the survivor to his true purpose."

The golden sea transformed.
Suddenly they stood in a gardenif gardens were made of floating continents
and trees that bore fruit of compressed starlight. Nanzo recognized it from the
clan's most forbidden texts: The Divine Tree Orchard, where tsutsuki gods
cultivated chakra fruit from devoured worlds.
Other figures materialized in the distanceIsshiki, Kaguya, Momoshiki,
Kinshiki, Urashikiall the tsutsuki who had descended upon the ninja world
throughout history. They were silhouettes, watching, waiting.
"The harvest approaches," Shibai said. "This worldyour precious 'Earth'
ripens. Kaguya's betrayal delayed it, but the fruit will be ready within your
lifetime."
He turned fully to Nanzo, and for a moment, he had a faceNanzo's own
face, but perfected, immortal, crowned with horns of pure chakra.
"Join us."
The offer resonated through every layer of Nanzo's being.
"Abandon this fragile mortal shell. I will remake you as my successora true
tsutsuki, not merely a diluted descendant. You will have immortality. You will
drink the chakra fruit's nectar and transcend death itself. Your Wave Style will
become Divine Wave Stylecapable of shattering dimensions, not merely
organs."
Shibai's eyesnow fully Rinnegan, now Byakugan, now something beyond
bothburned with terrible promise.
"In return, you will help us harvest. You will identify the strongest chakra
signatures on Earththe jinchriki, the Kage, the kekkei genkai masters. You
will prepare them for consumption. And when the Divine Tree blooms..."
He extended his hand.
"...you will be there to eat first."

Nanzo looked at the hand that had orchestrated his parents' murder.
He looked at the face that wore his own features like a mask.
He looked at the "god" who had reduced his mother's sacrifice to "delicious
waste."
And he laughed.
It started as a chuckledisbelieving, bitter. It grew into full-throated, hysterical
laughter that made the golden sea churn and the Divine Tree Orchard

real streamed down his face, until Shibai's expression shifted from
confidence to confusion to cold, ancient rage.
"You... find this amusing?" The god's voice was the pressure of collapsing
stars.
"Amusing?" Nanzo gasped, wiping phantom tears. "No. Pathetic. You're
pathetic."
He stepped forward, dream-form solidifying with sheer force of will, and spat
at Shibai's feetthe golden sand of this divine realm hissing where his
contempt landed.
"You think I want your immortality? Your 'Divine Wave Style'? I've seen what
godhood does to your kind. Kaguya went mad. Isshiki became a parasite.
Momoshiki was so desperate for power he ate his own partner."
He circled the god now, his voice dropping to a snarl that would have done
his wife proud.
"You abandoned your body to become... this." He gestured at Shibai's
shifting, formless presence. "Pure chakra? Pure will? You're nothing. You're a
ghost haunting your own descendants, too cowardly to die, too weak to truly
live. You whisper in dreams because you can't walk in reality. You 'encourage'
massacres because you're impotent to act directly."
Shibai's form darkened. The golden sea turned black. The distant tsutsuki
silhouettes began to move closer, sensing their progenitor's fury.
"You know what I think of when I wake up screaming?" Nanzo pressed,
relentless. "Not you. Not your 'divine' power. I think of my mother burning to
save me. I think of my father's last breath. I think of Nora eight years old

He leaned into Shibai's darkness, unafraid.
"They gave me mortality, you cosmic parasite. They gave me limits, and pain,
and lovereal love, not this... this consumption you call godhood. My wife
bites my neck and I feel alive. You haven't felt anything in millennia."
The god's rage was now a physical force, crushing, suffocating.
"You DARE"
"I DARE." Nanzo shouted back, his Wave Style resonance finally manifesting
in this dream-realm golden ripples of defiant chakra pushing back against
Shibai's darkness. "I am Nanzo Anitsu! Last heir of a clan YOU murdered!
Husband to the woman who defeated me! Master of Wave Style, Wind Style,
Gravity Manipulationtechniques I BUILT with physics and pain and choice!"
He straightened, and for a moment, he was more solid than the god before
him.
"I don't need your immortality. I don't want your successorship. I would rather
die in thirty minutes using Waver Mode to protect my wife than live forever as
your appetite." Shibai was silent.
Then, slowly, the darkness recededbut not in defeat. In promise.
"You refuse." It was not a question.
"Obviously."
"You mock me."
"Thoroughly."
Shibai's form condensed into something almost humanbeautiful, terrible,
smiling.
"Then remember this, little wave:" The god's voice dropped to a whisper that
would echo in Nanzo's skull for the rest of his life. "When the harvest comes.
When your precious wife's chakra ripens. When this world burns and the fruit
is plucked..."
He leaned close, breath that smelled of dead worlds and
aborted futures. "...I will come for you."
The smile widened, showing teeth that were also tombstones, also the
shards of the moon.
"And you will watch me consume everything you love, descendant. You will
watch because I will make you last. I will make you taste immortality as the
sole survivoragainbefore I unmake your very concept."
Nanzo felt himself being ejectedthe dream-realm rejecting his defiance,
Shibai's will thrusting him back toward consciousness.
"Sleep well, Nanzo Anitsu," the god's voice followed him through the void.
"Dream of waves. Dream of your mother's burning. Dream of me."

The Waking
Nanzo jolted awake.
His own gasp was loud in the dark bedroom. He was drenched in sweat, his
black wolf-hair plastered to his forehead, his yellow eyes wide and unseeing.
His heart hammered against his ribs like it wanted to escape.
For a terrible moment, he could still feel Shibai's presencecould still smell
the ozone-and-rot scent of the tsutsuki realm. His left hand went instinctively
to his neck, to the bite scar Karui had left there, grounding himself in physical
reality.
"Nanzo?"
Karui's voicesleep-rough, concernedcut through the lingering terror like a
blade through silk.
She was already sitting up, amber eyes alert despite having been deeply
asleep moments before. Jonin reflexes. Killer B's training. Her hand was on
the sword she kept beneath her pillow, but her eyes were scanning him
checking for injury, for Genjutsu, for threat.
"What happened?" she demanded. "You're shaking. Your chakra... it feels
wrong. Like it's still vibrating at some frequency I can't hear."
Nanzo opened his mouth.
Shibai tsutsuki contacted me. The god of our clan's secret bloodline. He
offered me immortality. I refused. He threatened to destroy everything I love.
He'll come for us. For you.
He looked at his wifehis wife, dark and beautiful and alive, wearing one of
his oversized shirts to bed, her red hair mussed from sleep, her wrist tattoo of
his face catching the moonlight.
He thought of Shibai's promise: "When your precious wife's chakra ripens."
He thought of her Final Resonanceburning herself to protect what she
loved.
"Nothing," he said.
The lie tasted like ash, but it tasted better than fear.
Karui's eyes narrowed. She knew him too wellknew every micro-
expression, every tells from their years of sparring, their marriage, their bond.
She knew he was lying.
But she also knew he would tell her when he was ready. Or when he needed
to.
She reached out, her dark hand finding his pale one in the darkness,

comfort, of presence, of I am here and I am real and I am not going

"Nothing," she repeated, not believing him for a second, but accepting the lie

She pulled him back down to the mattress, arranging them so that his head

"Sleep," she commanded softly, her hand in his hair. "Whatever it was, it can't
have you tonight. I won't
let it."
Nanzo closed his eyes.
In the darkness behind his lids, Shibai's final whisper still echoed: "I will come
for you."
But here, in the warmth of his wife's arms, with her heartbeat a steady drum

"Let him come."
He pressed closer to Karui, breathing in her scentlife, mortality, loveand

Chapter 9: The Mission to the Land of Waves
The assignment came through standard channels: investigate disturbances in
the Land of Waves, a small nation that had once been oppressed by the
criminal Gat but had since become a peaceful ally of the Hidden Leaf. Now,
something was disrupting their shipping lanes, sinking vessels without trace,
leaving no survivors.
Darui assigned the mission to Team Samui, with Nanzo attached as a
specialist consultant. It was the first time Karui would work with her old team
since her marriage, and she felt the complexity of the situation as they
gathered at the village gates.
Samui looked the samecool, professional, her blonde hair immaculate.
Omoi looked different, somehow older, his worried expression replaced by
something more settled. And Nanzo...
Nanzo wore his formal mission gear, the white armor of the Anitsu Clan
adapted for travel, his sword at his hip. He looked every inch the clan head,
the powerful shinobi, the man who had grown beyond the Prince she had first
defeated.
"Newlyweds on a mission together," Omoi said, his tone carefully neutral.
"This should be interesting. Or disastrous. Or interestingly disastrous."
"Shut up, Omoi," Karui said, but without heat. She was too focused on the
mission, on the reports of wave-based attacks that had drawn Darui's
attention and Nanzo's concern.
"The Land of Waves," Nanzo said, studying the map. "Appropriately named. If
our theoretical enemy is using wave-techniques, this environment would
amplify their power significantly."
"Or yours," Samui noted. "Your clan's abilities are wave-based as well, aren't
they?"
"Similar but distinct." Nanzo rolled the map, his expression serious. "Which is
why I'm concerned. If someone has developed a technique that mimics our
style, they could be using the ocean itself as a weapon. That level of
destruction would be... catastrophic."
They traveled in silence for the first day, moving through the forests that
separated Lightning from Water territories. Karui walked beside Nanzo, close
enough to support him if needed, far enough to maintain professional
distance in front of her team. It was a balance they were still learning.
That night, around the campfire, Omoi finally broke the tension.
"So," he said, roasting a fish on a stick with more attention than the task
required. "Marriage. How's that working out for you two?"
"Omoi," Samui warned.
"What? I'm curious! It's not every day your teammate marries the most
powerful clan head in the village. I have questions." He looked at Nanzo.
"Does she still call you Prince?"
Nanzo smiled, the expression transforming his face from intimidating to
approachable. "Only when she's annoyed with me. Which is frequently."
"And you let her?"
"I encourage it." Nanzo's eyes found Karui across the fire, warm with private
memory. "It reminds me of who I was, who I am, who I want to be. She keeps
me honest, Omoi-san. No one else in my life does that."
Karui felt her cheeks warm, grateful for the darkness that hid her blush. "He's
not so bad himself," she muttered. "For a Prince."
They laughed, the sound easing the tension, and for a moment they were just
four shinobi on a mission, partners in danger, bound by trust rather than
blood or law.
Then the wave hit.
It came without warninga wall of water rising from the nearby river, shaped
into a hand that reached for them with unmistakable malice. Nanzo moved
first, his hands forming seals that Karui didn't recognize, creating a counter-
wave that met the attack and dispersed it into harmless spray.
"Up!" he shouted. "Into the trees! It's coming from the water!"
They scrambled upward, finding perches in the high branches, scanning the
darkness for their attacker. The river below churned, foam rising, and from its
depths emerged a figure wrapped in seals and bandages, their chakra
signature distorted beyond recognition.
"Anitsu," the figure said, their voice bubbling like water through a drowning
throat. "We have waited for you. The heir of Shibai. The last carrier of true
wave."
"Who are you?" Nanzo demanded, his hands ready with seals.
"We are the Tide," the figure replied. "The ones who were forgotten when
your ancestor ascended. We who were left behind to drown in mortal flesh
while Shibai transcended. And we have come to claim what was promised
your blood, your power, your life as sacrifice to open the path."
The figure raised their hands, and the river responded, rising into serpents of
water that struck at the trees with crushing force. Nanzo countered with Wave
Style, his own vibrations disrupting the water's cohesion, but Karui saw the
strain on his facethis enemy was strong, their technique refined in ways
that suggested years of dedicated practice.
"Karui!" Nanzo called. "The seals on their chest! They're using stored chakra
to amplify the wavesif you can break the containment, you'll disrupt their
power!"
"On it!" She leaped from her branch, sword drawn, using the techniques she
had taught him and he had enhanced with physicscalculating angles, using
momentum, turning her body into a projectile that closed the distance before
the water-serpents could intercept.
The Tide-figure saw her coming and laughed, a gurgling sound. "The dark
wife! The pollution of purity! You think your steel can harm one who
commands the ocean itself?"
"My steel," Karui grunted, parrying a water-whip, "is the least of your worries."
She struck, not at the figure but at the riverbank beneath them, her chakra-
enhanced blade cutting through stone and earth, destabilizing the ground that
supported their position. The figure stumbled, their concentration breaking for
just a momentand in that moment, Nanzo struck.
Wave Style: Internal Resonance. A precise frequency that bypassed the
water defenses and struck directly at the seal-containment on the figure's
chest. There was a sound like breaking glass, and the stored chakra erupted
outward, throwing both combatants back.
Karui hit a tree, the impact driving breath from her lungs, but she forced
herself up, searching for Nanzo. She found him in the river shallows, his
white armor stained with mud, his hand extended toward the collapsing figure
of their enemy.
"Who sent you?" he demanded, his voice carrying the weight of clan head
authority. "Who else knows the secret of Shibai?"
The figure laughed, blood bubbling from beneath their bandages.
"Everyone... will know... soon. The Tide rises... Anitsu. You cannot stop... the
return. Your wife... your dark wife... will be the first to drown... in the wave of
your... ascension..."
They dissolved then, becoming water, becoming nothing, leaving only wet
bandages and the echo of their threat.
Karui stumbled to Nanzo's side, checking him for injuries, her hands shaking
with adrenaline and fear. "What did they mean? Ascending? Drowning?"
"I don't know." He stared at the empty bandages, his expression haunted.
"But I intend to find out. The Tide... they're connected to Shibai's original
followers. The ones who were left behind when my ancestor transcended. If
they're seeking revenge, seeking to force ascension through sacrifice..." He
looked at her, and she saw the fear in his eyes. "They want me to use the
Waver Mode, Karui. They want me to burn out, to become like Shibai, to
leave this world behind. And they think that threatening you is the way to
force that choice."
"Then we stop them." She helped him stand, her grip firm on his arm.
"Together. Before they can force anything."
"Together," he agreed. But his eyes remained on the water, where the
bandages floated like a warning, and she knew he was thinking of the
chamber deep beneath the compound, and the power that could save
everything at the cost of his life.

Chapter 10: The Tide Rises
The investigation led them to the Land of Waves' coast, to a village that had
been abandoned for years, ever since Gat's reign of terror. Now it was
occupied again, but not by living people. The buildings were filled with water,
shaped into forms that mimicked human habitationtables of ice, chairs of
compressed liquid, curtains of falling spray that somehow maintained their
form against gravity.
"The Tide's sanctuary," Samui observed, her voice low. "They've transformed
the entire village into a temple of water."
"It's beautiful," Omoi said, and he wasn't wrong. In the moonlight, the water-
structures glowed with an ethereal light, blue and green and silver. "And
completely terrifying."
Nanzo moved through the streets with the confidence of someone who
understood what they were seeing. "Wave resonance," he explained,
touching a pillar of spinning water that hummed beneath his fingers. "They're
using the same principles as my clan, but applied externally rather than
internally. Instead of manipulating their own chakra waves, they're
manipulating the waves in the environment. It's less powerful but more
versatile."
"Can you counter it?" Karui asked.
"Yes. But not without significant destruction." He looked at the water-
structures, at the artistry and the madness combined. "If I use my full power
here, I'll destroy the entire village. And possibly trigger geological instability
that could affect the whole region."
"Then we do this quietly," Samui decided. "Infiltration, not assault. Find their
leader, learn their plans, disrupt their operations with minimal collateral

"Agreed." Nanzo looked at Karui, a question in his eyes. "Can you handle

"Will be less effective, yes. But I'm not just lightning." She drew her sword,
feeling the balance of it, the weight that had become familiar as her own arm.
"I'm the woman who defeated you in a forest, remember? I don't need

He smiled, that rare expression that made her heart stutter. "I remember. I will
always remember."
They split up, Samui and Omoi taking the northern sector while Karui and
Nanzo moved toward the central structurea temple of water that rose higher
than the surrounding buildings, its spires reaching toward the moon like

The interior was a maze of liquid walls and floors that solidified only when
stepped upon. Karui moved carefully, her chakra control precise, maintaining
her balance on surfaces that shifted and flowed. Nanzo walked beside her
with easier confidence, his Wave Style allowing him to sense the stability of
each step before he took it.
"They know we're here," he murmured, his hand brushing hers in the
darkness. "The water is responding to our presence, carrying information to
the center."
"Then let's not keep them waiting."
They emerged into a central chamber, a cathedral of water where the

She was old, older than Nora, her skin wrinkled and pale, her eyesnot

"Nanzo," she said, her voice carrying the weight of tides. "Grandson of my

"Grandson?" Karui looked at Nanzo, saw the shock on his face.
"My father's sister," he whispered. "She was reported killed in the Second

"Not destroyed," the old woman said. "Transformed. We who were left behind
when Shibai called the worthywe found another path. The path of the Tide,

To make one of our blood transcend, as Shibai did, and open the path for all
of us."
"You want me to use the Waver Mode," Nanzo said. "To burn out my life and
become like Shibai."
"I want you to fulfill your destiny!" Umi's voice rose, the water responding to

Umi's eyes moved to Karui, and her expression became something cold and

Karui felt ice in her veins, but she didn't show fear. Instead, she stepped
forward, placing herself between Umi and Nanzo, her sword raised. "You

The water attacked.
Not as simple waves, but as shapeshands and teeth and crushing

Karui fought beside him, her sword cutting through water-forms that reformed
instantly, her body moving in the patterns she had taught him and they had
refined together. But it wasn't enough. The Tide had prepared for this, had

"Nanzo!" she called, parrying a water-spear. "We need to retreat, regroup!"
"We can't." He was breathing hard, his chakra reserves depleting rapidly. "If

"Then end it!" She grabbed his arm, forcing him to look at her. "Use what you
need to use. I trust you."
"I can't!" The desperation in his voice broke her heart. "If I use the Waver
Mode, I die. And I promised youI promised I wouldn't leave you. I won't
break that promise, Karui. Not even to win."
Umi laughed, the sound echoing through the water-cathedral. "Noble!
Foolish! You would let her die to keep your word? What kind of love is that?"
"The kind that trusts," Karui said. She turned to face Umi, her sword dropping
to her side, her stance opening in apparent surrender. "You want him to

everything that tied him to this worldincluding the desire to transcend."
"Philosophy!" Umi sneered. "Words to comfort the weak!"
"Truth to challenge the strong." Karui moved forward, walking through the

She reached Umi, close enough to strike, close enough to be struck. The old

"Kill me," Karui said, "and he will never ascend. He will destroy himself trying

But he will not become what you want. Because love isn't a chain, Umi. It's a

desperate fear of death."
Umi stared at her, and in the blue eyes, Karui saw something shift. Doubt.
Recognition. The first crack in sixty years of certainty.
"You... you truly believe this," Umi whispered.
"I truly live it." Karui held out her hand, not as a fighter but as a fellow human
being. "Come back with us. Let us help you find another way. Your family
Nanzo's familythought you were dead. They mourned you. They don't have
to lose you again."
For a moment, impossibly, Umi hesitated. The water around them calmed,
the storm pausing, possibility hanging in the balance.
Then the seal on Umi's chestthe same type that Nanzo had identified on
the earlier attackerbegan to glow red. Her eyes widened in terror.
"No," she gasped. "I didn't... I didn't trigger it..."
"Umi!" Nanzo lunged forward, his hands forming seals, trying to disrupt
whatever was happening. But he was too late, too depleted, too slow.
The seal exploded.
Not with fire, but with waterpure, concentrated, pressurized water that
expanded instantly to fill the chamber. Karui felt herself lifted, thrown, the
breath crushed from her lungs by the sudden pressure.
She saw Nanzo reaching for her, his mouth open in a scream she couldn't
hear, his yellow eyes wide with horror.
Then the water closed over her head, and everything went dark.

Chapter 11: The Drowning and the Rescue
Consciousness returned slowly, accompanied by pain and the desperate
need to breathe. Karui coughed, water pouring from her lungs, her body
convulsing as it fought to clear itself of liquid death.
"Stay with me," Nanzo's voice, raw and terrified. "Karui, stay with me.
Breathe. Just breathe."
She opened her eyes to see him above her, his white armor gone, his pale
skin covered in cuts and bruises, his hands pressing rhythmically on her
chest. They were on the shore somewhere, the moon still high, the water
lapping gently at their feet. The water-cathedral was gone, collapsed into the
sea, leaving only wet sand and debris.
"Umi?" she managed, her voice a rasp.
"Gone. The seal was a failsafetriggered remotely when she hesitated.
Whoever controls the Tide didn't want her to be reasoned with." Nanzo's
hands moved to her face, cradling it with desperate gentleness. "I thought I
lost you. The pressure, the water, I couldn't reach you in time. If Samui and
Omoi hadn't arrived when they did..."
"Samui?" Karui turned her head, saw her teammates approaching across the
beach, their own gear damaged, their expressions grim.
"We found their secondary base," Samui reported. "A command center.
Whoever is leading the Tide wasn't herethey're operating remotely, through
seals and proxies. But we found intelligence. Names, locations, their broader
plan."
"They're targeting all the hidden villages," Omoi added, his usual worry
replaced by something harder. "Not just Kumogakure. They have agents
everywhere, waiting to trigger wave-based catastrophes. Tsunamis,
earthquakes, chakra network disruptions. They want to force ascension on a
global scale kill enough people, cause enough destruction, that someone
somewhere will embrace the Waver Mode out of desperation."
"And open the path for all of them to transcend," Nanzo finished, his voice
hollow. "A apocalypse of waves, designed to create a god."
Karui forced herself to sit up, her body protesting every movement. "Then we
stop them. We find their leader, we disrupt their network, we prevent any of
this from happening."
"How?" Nanzo asked. "They're everywhere and nowhere. We don't even
know who the true leader is."
"We know they're afraid of reason." Karui grabbed his hand, squeezing it with
what strength she had. "Umi hesitated when I spoke to her. She was ready to
listen, to change, before the seal killed her. That means the Tide's ideology
isn't as solid as they want us to believe. There are cracks. Doubts. We find
those cracks and we widen them."
"Divide and conquer," Samui said, nodding slowly. "Turn their own members
against them."
"While we hunt their leadership," Omoi added. "Cut off the head, and the
body dies."
Nanzo was silent for a long moment, staring at the ocean where his great-
aunt had died. Then he nodded, his expression hardening into resolve. "We
return to Kumogakure. We brief Darui, we mobilize our network, we begin
systematic disruption of Tide operations worldwide. And we find their leader
whoever is pulling the strings, triggering the seals, forcing good people like
Umi to die rather than think for themselves."
He helped Karui stand, supporting her weight when her legs threatened to
give out. "Are you alright?" he asked softly, for her ears only.
"I will be." She leaned into him, accepting his strength, offering her own in
return. "But Nanzopromise me again. No matter what they do, no matter
how bad it gets, no Waver Mode. We find another way.
Together."
"I promise," he said. And this time, she believed him.

VOLUME III: THE WAVER'S CHOICE
---
Chapter 12: The War of Waves
Six months. Six months of covert operations, of hunting Tide cells across the
elemental nations, of disrupting their plans and saving their potential victims.
Six months of partnership tested in fire, of love growing stronger with each
challenge overcome.
Now they stood on the cliffs above Kumogakure, watching the storm gather
on the horizon. The Tide's final gambit. Their leader had been identifieda
man named Kaiy, once a scholar of the Hidden Mist, now obsessed with
achieving what Umi had failed to force. He had spent decades studying
Shibai's legacy, and he believed he had found a way to trigger mass
ascension without needing a willing sacrifice.
He needed only a focal point. A nexus of wave energy that could amplify his
technique across the entire world.
He needed Nanzo.
"He's coming here," Darui said, his Black Lightning crackling with suppressed
tension. "Our intelligence confirms it. He believes that if he can force Nanzo
into Waver Mode near the village, the resonance will trigger a chain reaction.
Every hidden village will experience wave-catastrophe simultaneously.
Millions will die. And in the chaos, someoneperhaps multiple someones
will embrace ascension out of desperation."
"Then we evacuate," Karui said. "Get everyone out of range."
"Two hundred kilometers," Nanzo whispered. "That's the Waver Mode's
range. We can't evacuate the entire continent."
"Then we stop him before he can force your hand." Karui turned to face her
husband, her partner, her love. "We fight him here, on our terms. And we win
without the Waver Mode."
"How?" Nanzo's voice was bleak. "He's studied my techniques. He knows my
weaknesses. He'll exploit the five-meter dead zone, force me into close
combat where I'm vulnerable, make me choose between death and
ascension."
"Then we don't give him the choice." Karui stepped closer, her hands on his
shoulders, her eyes locked on his. "We fight together. You and me. Long
range and close. Wave and steel. We show him what partnership really
means."
The storm hit at dawn.
Kaiy came walking across the water, the ocean itself parting before him, his
body wrapped in seals that glowed with sickly green light. He was younger
than they expected, his face unlined, his eyesthe blue of deep water, like
Umi'sbright with fanatical certainty.
"Nanzo Anitsu," he called, his voice carrying across the waves. "I offer you a
choice. Ascend willingly, become the god you were born to be, and save
those you love. Or resist, and watch me destroy everything you care about
until you have no choice left."
"There's always a choice," Nanzo replied, his own voice amplified by Wave
Style resonance. "You just don't like the ones that don't end with you getting
what you want."
Kaiy smiled, and the water rose behind him, forming into shapesgiants,
monsters, the entire ocean become an army. "Then let me narrow your
options."
The battle was unlike anything Karui had experienced. Kaiy didn't fight
directly; he commanded the environment, turning the sea itself into a weapon
that struck from all directions at once. Nanzo countered with Wave Style,
disrupting the water's coherence, creating zones of stability in the chaos, but
it was a losing proposition. For every wave he stopped, three more rose. For
every attack he deflected, Kaiy simply reshaped the water and struck again.
Karui fought through it, her sword cutting through water-forms, her body
moving in the patterns she had taught Nanzo, the partnership that made
them stronger than either alone. But she couldn't reach Kaiy. He stayed
safely distant, beyond her sword's reach, beyond even Nanzo's optimal
gravity range.
"He's wearing you down," she called to Nanzo, parrying a water-spear.
"Forcing you to expend chakra until you're desperate."
"I know." He was breathing hard, his white armor stained with salt and blood.
"He's trying to make me use the Waver Mode. He thinks that if he pushes me
hard enough, I'll choose ascension just to stop him."
"Will you?"
He looked at her, and she saw the exhaustion in his eyes, the temptation, the
desperate calculation of whether thirty minutes of godhood might be worth
the price.
"No," he said. "I promised. I promised you."
"Then trust me." She sheathed her sword, a gesture that made Kaiy pause,
that made Nanzo stare. "Trust me, and do exactly what I say."
She explained quickly, her voice low, her plan desperate and dangerous and
possibly suicidal. But Nanzo listened, and his eyes lit with understanding, and
when she finished, he kissed herhard, brief, a promise and a farewell in
one.
"Together," he said.
"Together," she agreed.
She ran.
Not away, but toward Kaiy, sprinting across the water's surface with chakra-
enhanced speed, closing the distance that had kept her from him. Kaiy
laughed, raising his hands to summon a wall of water that would crush her,
that would end this annoying gnat who thought she could challenge a god.
But Nanzo moved too.
Gravity Manipulation. The technique he had created, unique to him, that
could lock even gods in place. He activated it at maximum range, catching
Kaiy in the field, freezing him for one precious minute.
One minute. Sixty seconds. The same duration that had doomed him in the
forest, all those years ago.
Kaiy laughed, even as he couldn't move. "Fool! You know what this costs
you! Thirty-minute cooldown, no gravity, no wave style for fifteen minutes!
You'll be helpless!"
"I know," Nanzo said. He was running too, following Karui, closing the
distance to his own dead zone. "But I'm not helpless. I haven't been helpless
for a long time."
Karui reached Kaiy as the gravity field released. The water wall collapsed
without his direction, becoming simple ocean again. She was inside his
guard, inside the space where he had thought himself safe, and her sword
was already moving.
He tried to counter with water, with wave techniques, but she was too close,
too fast, too well-trained by the woman who had defeated the most powerful
clan head in Kumogakure. Her blade struck the seals on his chestnot to kill,
but to disrupt, to destroy the containment that allowed him to command the
ocean.
"No!" Kaiy screamed as his power unraveled. "You can't! I am the Tide! I am
the future!"
"You're a man who forgot how to be human," Karui said, her sword at his
throat. "And I'm the woman who remembers."
Nanzo reached them then, entering the five-meter zone where his long-range
techniques were useless, where he had once been completely vulnerable.
But he wasn't vulnerable anymore. He had trained for this. He had prepared.
Close combat. Taijutsu. The sword techniques that Karui had taught him,
enhanced by his understanding of physics and force. He struck Kaiy
precisely, scientifically, targeting nerve clusters and pressure points with a
precision that no pure warrior could match.
Kaiy fell, his power broken, his army of water collapsing back into the ocean,
the storm dissipating as suddenly as it had come.
They stood over him, dark and pale, stubborn and scientific, partners in truth.
"You could kill me," Kaiy gasped, blood mixing with salt water on his lips.
"End the threat."
"We could," Nanzo agreed. "But that would make us like you. Believing that
ends justify means, that power is the only solution." He knelt, placing a seal
on Kaiy's forehead that would suppress his chakra, render him harmless.
"You're going to live. You're going to face judgment for your crimes. And
maybe, in time, you'll learn what Umi almost learnedthat ascension isn't
something you force. It's something you earn, through living fully, through
loving deeply, through choosing humanity over godhood every single day."
Karui helped him stand, their hands finding each other automatically. "We did
it," she said, wonderingly. "Without the Waver Mode. Without anyone dying."
"We did it," he agreed. "Together."
Behind them, the sun broke through the clouds, illuminating Kumogakure and
the ocean beyond. The Tide was defeated. The threat was ended. And they
were still alive, still human, still choosing each other against all the forces that
wanted to tear them apart.

Chapter 13: "The Gravity of Wolves"
The morning mist clung to the Anitsu Clan compound like a shroud, curling
around the ancient stone walls that had survived the Second Great Ninja
War. Nanzo stood at the eastern gate, his travel pack light, his expression
carefully neutral. At twenty years old, he carried the weight of a clan that had
been reduced to five living souls, a Kekkei Genkai that could liquefy organs
with a thought, and a secret so terrible that only his wife knew its full
measure.
"You're certain about this?" Karui asked.
She stood close enough that he could smell herdark skin warmed by the
morning sun, the faint metallic tang of the sword oil she used on her katana,
something uniquely her that he had once described, privately, as his
addiction. Her amber eyes caught the light, sharp and searching. Not yellow
like his. Not pure like the blood descendants of his clan. Beautiful precisely
because they were different.
"It's not a messenger mission," Nanzo said, adjusting his forehead protector.
He no longer wore the Kumogakure bandhis status as clan head
superseded such identifiersbut he carried it in his pack. A formality for
crossing borders. "The Raikage requested someone of appropriate rank to
discuss Chnin Exam coordination with Konohagakure. Given my... unique
position."
"Unique position." Karui's voice was dry. "You mean the fact that you're
beyond Kage-level and could theoretically destroy their entire village if they
annoy you?"
"I mean the fact that I'm clan head and therefore politically relevant." He
reached out, his pale fingers tracing the line of her jaw, feeling the warmth
there. The contrast that Nora Anitsuwaiting somewhere inside the
compound, maintaining perfect surface politenessfound so disturbing. "And
yes. That."
Karui caught his hand, her grip strong. The grip of a woman who had bitten
his neck while he was helpless, who had trained him to wield a blade when
his long-range techniques failed, who wore his face tattooed on her wrist as
permanent declaration.
"You're bored," she said. It wasn't an accusation. It was understanding.
"Curious. You want to see the world beyond Cloud's borders."
"I want to see if they measure up," he admitted, smiling slightly. "To you. To
this." He gestured vaguely at the compound, at the life they had built
togetherhim, the orphan raised by a maid he called "Mom" in private,
married to the woman who had defeated him through sheer stubborn refusal
to die.
Karui's expression softened in a way that only he ever saw. The fierce,
combative kunoichi who had beaten Naruto Uzumaki bloody, who had faced
down Sasuke's crimes with fists instead of words, who carried the "ugly dark"
label from the insecure white minority as a badge of defiant prideshe
softened for him.
"Come back," she said simply. "I don't care if you learn their secrets. I don't
care if you fight their Kage. Just come back."
"I will," he promised. And because Nora was watching from a window,
maintaining the fiction of distance, he added formally: "Take care of the
compound, Nora-san. I'll return within the week."
"Travel safely, Nanzo-sama," came the proper response.
But Karui saw the way his eyes lingered, the subtle warmth that spoke of
private momentsof him calling that woman "Mom," of kissing her cheek in
gratitude for raising him, of the complex bond between a boy who had lost
everything and the woman who had given him back his future. Karui
understood it. Respected it, even, though she knew what Nora truly thought
when she looked at her daughter-in-law.
Ugly dark. Dark lips. Ugly body shape. Someone who might scare him if he
truly saw her clearly.
Let her think it. Karui was the 70% majority in this village. The Raikage was
dark. Killer B was dark. Darui was dark. She was the standard, not the
exception. The white minority's discomfort was their own weakness.
"White is ugly," Karui murmured, too quietly for anyone but Nanzo to hear.
"Dark is beautiful and sexy."
He laughed, pressing his forehead to hers. "And I am the luckiest man in any
village, because I know it's true."
Then he was gone, moving with the casual speed of someone who could, if
he chose, cross the distance between villages in minutes rather than days.
But he took his time. A journey, not a mission. A chance to breathe air that
didn't carry the weight of his clan's extinction, his parents' death in the
Second War, the burden of being the only one who knew about Shibai
tsutsuki.
The wind carried him southeast, toward the Land of Fire.
---
Konohagakure was... green.
Nanzo had prepared himself for the differenceKumogakure sat high in the
mountains, all stone and lightning and thin air, while the Hidden Leaf nestled
in a forest basin, lush and sprawling. But preparation was not experience. He
found himself lingering at the gates longer than necessary, watching the flow
of people, noting the demographic balance that was so different from his
home.
Here, the dark-skinned majority of Cloud was not present. Here, he was not
the statistical minority, the rare "Prince" prized for his pale skin and yellow
eyes. Here, he was simply... foreign. Powerful, certainly the guards at the
gate had sensed that immediately, their hands drifting toward weapons before
discipline reasserted itself. But not rare.
It was oddly liberating.
His meeting with Kakashi Hatake was scheduled for the following morning.
Official business. Chnin Exam coordination, joint training exercises, the
endless diplomacy of villages pretending they weren't measuring each other
for weaknesses. Nanzo could have handled it in an hour and returned home.
Instead, he checked into a guest house near the village center, deposited his
pack, and went walking.
The Inuzuka compound lay northwest of the main village, separated from the
Aburame clan by training grounds and forest buffer. Nanzo found it by
following his nosethe distinct scent of canines, of wildness, of a clan that
refused full domestication. The compound itself was low-slung and practical,
designed for beings with four legs as much as two.
He was watching a young boyKiba, he would later learntraining with a
puppy when she found him.
"You're trespassing."
The voice came from above. Nanzo looked up, his yellow eyes tracking the
figure perched on a branch fifteen feet overhead. She was... feral. That was
the word that came to mind. Long brown hair pulled back in a spiky tail,
vertical slit pupils that marked her Inuzuka blood, red fang tattoos carved into
her cheeks. She wore a standard flak jacket over a cropped top, her midriff
exposed, her posture that of a predator measuring prey.
"Nanzo Anitsu," he said, offering a slight bow. "From Kumogakure. I
apologizeI was curious about your compound's architecture. The way
you've integrated living spaces with kennel facilities is... efficient."
She dropped from the branch, landing without sound. A large black hound
emerged from the shadows beside her, hackles rising, intelligent eyes fixed
on the intruder.
"Architecture," the woman repeated, her voice rich with skepticism. "You're
the Cloud Prince. The whiteskinned miracle from the minority clan. Married to
that red-haired berserker who beat the hell out of Naruto Uzumaki during the
Summit."
Nanzo felt his eyebrows rise. "You know of my wife?"
"Know of her?" The woman laughed, sharp and barking. "Tsume Inuzuka.
Tokubetsu jnin. I was at the Summit, standing guard. Saw your girl work.
Fierce. Stubborn." Tsume's eyes narrowed, her nose twitching. "She smells
like you. Deeply. Permanently. You wear each other like armor."
"We're married," Nanzo said simply.
"Obviously." Tsume circled him, and he let her, standing still as her hound
Kuromaru, he would learn growled low in his throat. "So what does a
beyond-Kage-level shinobi want in my woods, Anitsu? Because you reek of
power. Wave chakra, wind manipulation, something elsegravity? You're a
walking natural disaster wearing human skin."
Nanzo considered lying. Considered the diplomatic response, the careful
deflection. Instead, he found himself telling the truth.
"I'm bored," he said. "And curious. And I have three days before my official
business requires me to return home. I thought... perhaps... someone here
might spar with me. Someone who wouldn't hold back because of my rank."
Tsume stopped circling. Her slit pupils dilated slightly, and he realized she
was scenting himnot just his chakra, but his emotional state. The loneliness
he carried. The weight of being the last hope of a nearly extinct clan. The
desperate, consuming love he felt for the woman who had defeated him. "You
want to fight," she said slowly. "Not to win. Just to... move."
"Yes."
She studied him for a long moment. Then she smiled, all teeth, wild and
dangerous.
"Tomorrow. Dawn. The training grounds behind the compound. Bring your
swordI've heard you learned kenjutsu from your wife. I want to see if the
rumors are true."
She turned and walked away, her hound following, leaving Nanzo standing in
the gathering dusk with his heart beating faster than it had in months.

They met as promised, and Tsume Inuzuka did not hold back.
She came at him with the Fang Passing Fang, her body rotating at high
speed, creating a destructive drill of chakra and flesh. Nanzo sidestepped, his
Wind Style: Paralyze Sword flashing outnot to strike, but to deflect. The
wind pressure carved a furrow in the earth where she had been, and Tsume
laughed, the sound wild and genuine.
"Good! Again!"
They fought for an hour. Nanzo restricted himselfno Wave Style (fifteen-
minute cooldown, too valuable for sparring), no gravity manipulation (thirty-
minute cooldown, and he would not use such a technique on an ally). He
fought with taijutsu and kenjutsu, the arts Karui had drilled into him after their
marriage, and found himself challenged in ways he hadn't expected.
Tsume was fast. Faster than anyone in Cloud except perhaps the Raikage
himself. Her fighting style was animalistic, unpredictable, leveraging her
clan's enhanced senses and physical capabilities. She bit, clawed, used her
entire body as a weapon. And she was intelligentreading his patterns,
adapting to his wind techniques, forcing him to think in real-time about angles
and force distribution.
"You fight like you're calculating," she observed, breaking away to catch her
breath. Sweat gleamed on her skin, her chest heaving, her eyes bright with
combat high. "Every move. Every counter. Physics?"
"Academic background," Nanzo confirmed, lowering his sword. "I was... not
always skilled in close combat. It was my weakness. My wife trained me."
"Karui." Tsume tested the name. "The dark beauty who claimed the white
prince."
"She defeated me completely," Nanzo said, and there was no shame in his
voice, only profound respect. "Exploited my cooldowns, closed to close range
where my techniques were useless, and bit my neck while I was helpless.
Left a permanent mark."
Tsume's eyes dropped to his throat, to the scar visible above his collar. Her
expression shifted, something complicated moving through her features. "She
marked you. Like a mate."
"Like a victor," Nanzo corrected gently. "Like the woman who saw through my
arrogance and made me worthy of being her husband."
They sat together afterward, sharing water from his canteen. Tsume told him
about her clanthe Inuzuka partnership with ninken, the enhanced senses,
the wild reputation that masked deep loyalty. She told him about her children,
Kiba and Hana, raised alone after she had driven their father away with her
intensity.
"He couldn't handle me," she said, staring at the trees. "Said I was too much.
Too loud, too aggressive, too wild. As if I should apologize for being what I
am."
"You shouldn't," Nanzo said quietly.
"No?" Tsume turned to look at him, her slit pupils catching the morning light.
"You're the rare white prize of your village. You could have had delicate, pale,
demure. Instead you chose fierce, dark, stubborn. Why?"
Nanzo was quiet for a long moment. When he spoke, his voice was soft with
memory. "She showed me that I was the minority. Not just in numbersin
thinking. I believed my pale skin made me special. She showed me that dark
is beautiful, that stubbornness is strength, that love isn't about rarity or status.
She is the majority in Kumogakure. The Raikage is dark. Killer B is dark.
Darui is dark. I was clinging to an illusion of superiority because I was afraid
of being ordinary."
He looked at Tsume, seeing the way her hands tightened on her water bottle,
the defensive set of her shoulders. "You are not 'too much,' Inuzuka-san. You

Tsume's breath caught. For a momentjust a momenther wild mask
slipped, and Nanzo saw the woman beneath. The mother who worried she
was failing her children. The warrior who had fought Pain's assault and
carried the scars. The lonely heart that had given up on being truly seen.
"You're dangerous," she whispered. "Not because of your power. Because of
how you look at people."
"Then look back," he said. "See me. Not the Cloud Prince. Not the weapon.
Just... a man who understands physics and gravity and the weight of being
alone."
They sat there until the sun cleared the trees, two predators acknowledging
each other across a gulf of circumstance and loyalty.

The official meeting with Kakashi Hatake took ninety minutes. Nanzo
extended his stay by three days, citing "additional diplomatic requirements"
that existed only in his imagination. No one questioned him. No one dared.
He spent every morning with Tsume.
They developed a routine. Dawn sparring, pushing each other to limits that
left them both bruised and exhilarated. Midday meals, sharing intelligence
about their respective villagescarefully, legally, nothing that would constitute
treason, but the kind of professional exchange that built trust between allies.
Afternoons, he would explore Konoha while she handled clan duties, and
they would meet again at dusk, on the roof of the Inuzuka compound, to
watch the sunset and talk.
He told her things he had told no one except Karui.
About his parents' death in the Second War, when he was ten. About being
raised by Nora, the maid who was more mother than servant, who had
trained him in Wave Style control while grieving the clan's destruction. About
the secret of Shibai tsutsuki, the divine origin of his bloodline, the god-level
power that lived in his cells.
"I have a technique," he said one evening, his voice barely audible. "Waver
Mode. It gives me true godhood for thirty minutes. Control over all waves
within two hundred kilometers. The ability to kill anyone instantly, to stop even
other gods, to move at wave propagation speed. And at the end of those
thirty minutes... I die. Automatically. Irrevocably."
Tsume was silent for a long time. Then: "Have you ever used it?"
"No. And I never will, if I can help it. Because of her." He touched the scar on
his neck unconsciously. "Karui knows. She guards my emotional state, my
trauma, my despair. She won't let me use it. She says... she says I can't
leave her alone in the world. That the orphan clan head who lost everything
deserves to keep what he's found."
"She's right," Tsume said fiercely. "You can't die. Not when you've finally
learned how to live."
She told him her secrets in return. About scaring away her children's father,
not through malice but through the sheer intensity of her being. About the
loneliness of raising Kiba and Hana alone, of watching them grow into
exceptional shinobi and wondering if they would forgive her for being too wild,
too much. About the nights she spent on this very roof, staring at the stars,
wondering if she was destined to always be alone.
"You're not alone," Nanzo said, and the words hung between them, heavy
with meaning they both pretended not to hear.
On the fourth night, it rained. They took shelter in a storage shed behind the
compound, the space small and close, smelling of dog food and training
equipment. Tsume's shoulder pressed against his, her warmth bleeding
through their wet clothes.
"Tell me about her," Tsume said suddenly. "Karui. Tell me what you love."
Nanzo closed his eyes, and he could see her perfectly. Red hair like fire.
Amber eyes like captured sunlight. Dark skin that glowed with health and
vitality, that she oiled to make richer, that she wore like armor against the
white minority's whispers.
"Everything," he said simply. "The way she refuses to back down from any
fight. The way she touches her wrist tattoo when she's thinking of me. The
way she sleepsdeep and heavy, trusting me to guard her. The way she

said I was ridiculous. But it's true. She grounds me. She makes the weight of
being Nanzo Anitsu bearable." "She's lucky," Tsume whispered.
"I'm luckier." He opened his eyes, turned his head, and found her face inches
from his. The rain drummed against the roof, a private percussion for this

"Don't," she breathed. "Don't say my name like that unless you mean to
do something about it." "I shouldn't"
"No. You shouldn't." Her eyes were wild, desperate, hungry. "You have a wife
who defeated you, who marked you, who wears your face on her skin. You
have a love that transformed you from arrogance to worth. I have nothing but
my clan and my children and this roof where I come to be alone. We
shouldn't. We can't."
But she didn't move away.
And Nanzo, who had learned from Karui that love was not about should or
shouldn't, about rules or expectations, but about the true, stubborn,
