Fifteen years old. Born the year after his marriage to Karui, when they were
both still young and fierce and desperately in love. She had his wild hair, her
mother's dark skina beautiful blend that made the old white minority
whisper and the new generation stare in awe. She had mastered Wave Style
by age ten, Wind Style by twelve, and was currently trying to convince him to
teach her Gravity Manipulation despite his refusal.
She was everything. She was why he had never used Waver Mode. She was
why he woke up every morning and chose to live.
She was also, though he would never say it aloud, named for the chief queen
of Lord Anitsu himself a secret between him and Karui, a promise that their
bloodline would endure with dignity and grace.
"No," Nanzo said.
The word was soft. Final.
A's eyes widened. Darui sat up straighter. Omoi's hand twitched toward his
swordinstinct, not threat.
"Excuse me?" A's voice was dangerous.
Nanzo turned from the window. His yellow eyesthose pure Anitsu eyes that
marked him as true blood held no hesitation.
"I said no."
He walked to the desk, placing both hands on it, leaning into Darui's space
with the casual confidence of a man who knew he could kill everyone in this
room before they blinkedand chose not to.
"I am not the Raikage. I will never be the Raikage."
"Give me one reason," A growled. "One good reason why the strongest
shinobi in our village's history refuses to lead it."
Nanzo smiled. It was not a kind smile. It was the smile of the boy who had
watched his parents die, who had been raised by an eight-year-old survivor,
who had married the woman who bit his neck and made him whole.
"My job is not to protect this village," he said quietly. "My job is to protect my
clan. My family."
He straightened, stepping back.
"The Raikage protects everyone. The Raikage sits in meetings. The Raikage
signs treaties and balances budgets and plays politics with the Daimy." His
voice hardened. "The Raikage dies of stress before age sixty, or dies in battle
protecting abstract concepts like 'the village' and 'the will of the people.'"
He looked at Awho had lost his arm to Sasuke, who had lost his brother to
war, who had aged decades in years.
He looked at Daruiwho had never wanted the hat, who had taken it from
duty, whose hair turned gray with the weight.
"I am beyond Kage level," Nanzo said. "Beyond world level. I have
techniques that could destroy nations. I have secrets that could unmake
reality. And I will not waste that power on administrative duties."
He turned to the window again, looking at his compound.
"My daughter is fifteen. Do you know what that means? It means she's old
enough to be targeted. Old enough to be used as leverage against me. Old
enough to be killed to hurt me."
His hand tightened on the windowsill. The glass vibratedWave Style
unconscious activation.
"The Uchiha who murdered my parentsFugaku's strike teamthey came for
me when I was one year old. They came because I was the heir. Because I
mattered."
He turned back, and his eyes were hard.
"I will not give the world another reason to target my child. I will not make her
the daughter of the Raikagethe political symbol, the assassination target,
the hostage-in-waiting. I will not leave her mother alone to raise her while I
attend Kage summits. I will not die in office and leave them both
unprotected."
The room was silent.
"My place is with them," Nanzo said. "Not here. Not wearing that hat."
Darui stood slowly. "Nanzo... we need you. The village"
"The village has you," Nanzo interrupted, but gently. "It has A-sama's
counsel. It has Killer B. It has the next generation."
He turned, and his eyes found Omoi.
The cautious boy. The overthinker. The one who had once seemed so weak
compared to Nanzo's overwhelming power.
But Omoi had grown. Omoi had served. Omoi had demonstrated something
Nanzo never could conviction without power, leadership without god-level
techniques, the ability to inspire through words and steadiness rather than
fear and awe.
"Give it to him," Nanzo said.
Omoi's eyes widened. "What?"
"The Sixth Raikage position. Give it to Omoi."
"He's a bodyguard!" A protested. "Reliable, yes, but"
"He's exactly what the village needs," Nanzo said, cutting across the former
Raikage without hesitation. "Someone who thinks before acting. Someone
who values every life, not just victory. Someone who won't rely on
overwhelming power to solve every problembecause he doesn't have
overwhelming power. He has to be smart. He has to be careful. He has to be
good."
He walked to Omoi, stopping before him.
"You were Karui's teammate," Nanzo said quietly. "You watched her chase
me. You watched her defeat me. You know what it means to see strength
where others see weakness."
Omoi swallowed. "Nanzo-sama... I'm not"
"You are," Nanzo said. "You've been preparing for this your whole life, even if
you didn't know it. Every cautious decision, every overthought plan, every
time you chose protection over aggressionthat was leadership."
He placed a hand on Omoi's shoulder.
"I will serve the village as I always havefrom the shadows, from the
battlefield, from the place where my power is needed most. But the hat? The
administration? The politics?"
He squeezed, and Omoi felt the restraint therethe god-level power held
back by sheer will. "That's yours. If you'll take it."
---
The Decision
A looked at Darui. Darui looked at A.
Something passed between themthe understanding of two men who had
worn the weight, who recognized that Nanzo was right, even if they hated it.
"Omoi," Darui said slowly. "Do you accept?"
Omoi looked at Nanzoat the man who had just declined the highest honor
in the village to protect his family. At the beyond-world-level shinobi who saw
more strength in caution than in power.
He thought of Samui, still missing, her fate unknown. He thought of Karui,
who had chosen love over village duty in her own way. He thought of his own
paththe careful steps, the worried plans, the constant fear of making
mistakes.
And he thought: Maybe caution is exactly what the village needs.
"I accept," Omoi said, his voice steadier than he felt. "But on one condition."
Nanzo raised an eyebrow.
"You teach me," Omoi said. "Not Wave StyleI know I can't learn that. But
strategy. Physics. How to think like you. How to protect without destroying."
Nanzo smiledreally smiled, the one that reached his eyes.
"Done."
He turned back to the window, looking at his compound, where a girl with red-
streaked black hair and golden eyes was probably training too hard and
worrying her mother.
"My daughter needs her father present," he said softly. "Not a legend. Not a
Kage. Just... present."
He walked to the door, pausing only to look back at the three men who would
shape the village's future.
"Call me when the world is ending. For everything else..."
The gravity in the room shiftedjust for a moment, just enough to remind
them what he was. "...Omoi will handle it."
---
Epilogue: The Compound
Nanzo walked home through streets that parted for him without him asking.
Villagers bowednot because he was Raikage, but because he was Nanzo
Anitsu. The man who had refused godhood twiceonce from Shibai
tsutsuki, once from his own village.
The man who chose family over power.
He found them in the training courtyard. Karuithirty-four, still fierce, still
beautiful, her dark skin gleaming with sweat as she corrected their daughter's
sword stance.
And herfifteen years of fire and waves and stubbornness. She had her
mother's red hair, her father's wildness, her grandmother Nyoko's medical
intuition, and her own unique brilliance.
She looked up as he entered, yellow eyes lighting up.
"Father! Did you"
"No," he said, knowing what she asked. "I'm not Raikage."
She deflated, then caught her mother's lookthe slight smile, the knowing
eyes.
"But... why?" she asked. "You're the strongest. Everyone knows it."
Nanzo walked to her, placing a hand on her headstill a gesture of affection,
even if she was nearly as tall as him now.
"Because my job is here," he said. "Protecting you. Protecting your mother.
Protecting our clan."
He looked at Karui, who watched him with amber eyes full of understanding.
She knew. She had always known. From the night she bit his neck to this
moment, she had known that his power was never for the village's throneit
was for them.
"Besides," Nanzo added, ruffling his daughter's hair. "Someone has to teach
you Gravity Manipulation. And I can't do that if I'm stuck in Kage meetings all
day."
She squealedactually squealed, all teenage coolness forgottenand
hugged him with the strength of a girl who had inherited her mother's
stubbornness and her father's chakra reserves.
Karui joined them, her arm sliding around Nanzo's waist, her head resting on
his shoulder as their daughter chattered about training schedules and physics
equations and finally, finally learning the technique that made her father
legendary.
"Omoi?" Karui asked softly, too quiet for their daughter to hear.
"Omoi," Nanzo confirmed. "Sixth Raikage."
"Good," Karui said. "He's cautious. He'll keep the village safe without
breaking it."
She looked up at him, amber eyes meeting yellow.
"And you?"
Nanzo smiled, pulling her closer, feeling their daughter's excited warmth
between them.
"I'm exactly where I need to be."
Above them, storm clouds gathered over Kumogakurebut in the Anitsu Clan
compound, there was only warmth, and love, and the quiet power of a man
who had chosen mortality over godhood, family over legend, and home over
glory.

EPILOGUE: THE WAVERS OF TOMORROW
Twenty years later, a young woman stood on the training grounds of the
Hidden Cloud Village, her skin a rich brown that matched her mother's, her
eyes the distinctive yellow of the Anitsu Clan bloodline that she had inherited
from her father. She held a sword in one hand and formed seals with the
other, combining close combat and Wave Style in a way that would have
been impossible for any previous generation.
"Focus, Narui!" called her mother, Karui, now the head of the Anitsu Clan's
combat division, her red hair streaked with silver but her body still powerful
and quick. "Your stance is drifting!"
"Yes, mother," Narui replied, adjusting her position. She knew better than to
argueher mother had defeated the most powerful shinobi in the village
through sheer stubbornness, and she had passed that stubbornness on to
her daughter.
From the balcony above, Nanzo watched them train, his own hair now
completely white, his eyes still bright with the intelligence that had made him
legendary. He was no longer clan headthat responsibility had passed to
Narui five years ago, when he had finally accepted that retirement was not
the same as surrender.
Nora sat beside him, ancient and frail but still present, her hand in his. She
had never fully overcome her prejudice, never fully embraced the dark future
that Karui represented. But she had learned to love her granddaughter, to
take pride in Narui's strength, to find a peace that had eluded her for most of
her life.
"She's good," Nora said, her voice thin but clear. "The combination of styles...
it's what you always envisioned, isn't it? The future you fought for."
"It is," Nanzo agreed. "Wave and steel. Physics and passion. The best of both
of us."
"And the Waver Mode?" Nora asked, the question she had avoided for
decades. "Does she know?"
"She knows." Nanzo's expression grew serious. "And she has sworn, as I did,
to find another way. To trust her partners, to fight together, to never choose
solitary godhood over shared humanity."
"Do you think she'll keep that promise?"
"I think," Nanzo said, watching his daughter move through forms that
combined his scientific precision with her mother's fierce grace, "that she will
have to face her own trials, her own temptations, her own version of the
choice I faced. And I think she will be stronger for having seen what love can
build, what partnership can achieve, what stubborn refusal to give up can
accomplish."
Karui looked up then, meeting his eyes across the distance, and smiledthe
same smile that had first made him feel seen, that had transformed him from
a prisoner of purity into a man who understood what it meant to be truly alive.
"Come down!" she called. "Your daughter wants to show you her new
technique!"
Nanzo rose, helping Nora to her feet, and together they descended to the
training grounds where the future was being forged in sweat and laughter and
love.
The waves continued, as they always had, as they always would. But now
they carried something new. Something that had been built by a Prince and a
stubborn girl, by teeth marks and training sessions, by the courage to choose
love over fear, again and again, until the choice became a life, and the life
became a legacy.
The Wavers of Kumogakure had changed the world. And they were only
beginning.
